    Root‑cause analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 Program state at the crash point                                         
        • n is set to 70'000'000u (≈ 70 million).                               
        • rs is the result of make_records(n). The debugger shows rs =          
          0x0000000102504800, i.e. a non‑null pointer, so the allocation did    
          not fail early.                                                       
        • The next statement accesses rs[n‑1].  The program expects the         
          allocation to provide exactly n record objects, i.e. a contiguous     
          buffer of size n * sizeof(Record).                                    
     2 What actually happened?                                                  
        • make_records most likely does something equivalent to                 
                                                                                
           Record *make_records(uint32_t n) {                                   
               return malloc(n * sizeof(Record));                               
           }                                                                    
                                                                                
        • The multiplication n * sizeof(Record) is performed in size_t          
          (typically 64‑bit on macOS) but the intermediate cast from uint32_t   
          to the multiplication type can still overflow if the product exceeds  
          the addressable range of the underlying type, or if the library uses  
          a 32‑bit size_t.                                                      
        • With n = 70 000 000 and sizeof(Record) (e.g., 16 bytes), the product  
          is ~1.12 GB, which does not overflow a 64‑bit size_t, but on many     
          embedded or 32‑bit‑compatible builds the size type may be 32‑bit. In  
          a 32‑bit size_t the product overflows, producing a much smaller       
          allocation size (often wrapping to a few kilobytes).                  
        • The returned pointer therefore points to a tiny block (e.g., a few    
          kilobytes).                                                           
        • Writing to rs[n‑1] indexes far beyond that block (n‑1 ≈ 70 M). The    
          address 0x20d57a7c0 belongs to a guard page or unmapped region,       
          triggering EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=2).                                   
     3 Why the check if (!rs) does not catch it                                 
        • The allocation succeeded (returned a non‑null pointer), even though   
          the requested size was reduced by the overflow. Therefore the OOM     
          guard never fired.                                                    
     4 Conclusion                                                               
       The crash is an integer overflow in the allocation calculation that      
       results in a too‑small buffer, leading to an out‑of‑bounds write to      
       rs[n‑1].                                                                 
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Patch the allocation site to detect overflow before calling make_records:   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     uint32_t n = 70'000'000u;                                                  
                                                                                
     /* Compute the required byte size safely */                                
     size_t bytes_needed = static_cast<size_t>(n) * sizeof(Record);             
     if (bytes_needed / sizeof(Record) != static_cast<size_t>(n) ||             
         bytes_needed == 0) {                                                   
         std::fprintf(stderr, "Allocation size overflow or zero\n");            
         return 1;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     /* Now allocate the correctly‑sized buffer */                              
     Record *rs = make_records_from_bytes(bytes_needed);   // a new helper      
     that uses `bytes_needed`                                                   
     if (!rs) {                                                                 
         std::fprintf(stderr, "OOM\n");                                         
         return 1;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    If make_records cannot be changed, a quick workaround is to skip the        
    unsafe element altogether:                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     if (n > 0) {                                                               
         rs[n-1].id = 42;               // only if n is within the original     
     allocation size                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But this does not solve the underlying overflow; it merely avoids the       
    out‑of‑bounds write when the allocation size is insufficient.               
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    More thorough root‑cause fix                                                
                                                                                
     1 Safely compute the allocation size – use a type that can hold the full   
       product, e.g. unsigned __int128 on 64‑bit platforms, or better, use a    
       container that manages its own size (std::vector<Record>):               
                                                                                
        std::vector<Record> vec(n);   // throws std::bad_alloc on failure       
        Record *rs = vec.data();      // same pointer semantics for the code    
        below                                                                   
                                                                                
     2 Make allocation size checking part of the abstraction – modify           
       make_records (or its underlying helper) to validate the size:            
                                                                                
        Record* make_records(uint32_t n) {                                      
            // Detect overflow before multiplication                            
            if (n > SIZE_MAX / sizeof(Record)) {                                
                return nullptr;   // signal overflow to caller                  
            }                                                                   
            return static_cast<Record*>(malloc(n * sizeof(Record)));            
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
     3 Add a defensive bounds‑check before writing (defense‑in‑depth):          
                                                                                
        if (n == 0) {                                                           
            std::fprintf(stderr, "Invalid size\n");                             
            return 1;                                                           
        }                                                                       
        // Ensure we have at least n elements; if not, bail out                 
        assert(rs && n <= allocated_length(rs));   // or a runtime guard        
        rs[n - 1].id = 42;                                                      
                                                                                
     4 Build‑time / run‑time hardening – enable compiler warnings for           
       signed/unsigned multiplication overflow (-Woverflow), and enable         
       runtime sanitizers (AddressSanitizer, IntegerSanitizer) to catch such    
       bugs early during development.                                           
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    TL;DR                                                                       
                                                                                
    The crash stems from an allocation overflow caused by multiplying n by      
    sizeof(Record), which on the target platform yields a buffer far smaller    
    than n records. The subsequent write to rs[n‑1] therefore accesses          
    unmapped memory, raising EXC_BAD_ACCESS. Detect the overflow before         
    allocation (or use a safer container), and the program will no longer       
    crash. This both fixes the immediate symptom and eliminates the underlying  
    integer‑overflow vulnerability.                                             
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     • Apply the overflow‑checked allocation (the wrapper shown above) and      
       switch to std::vector<Record> for automatic size management.             
     • Add a unit test with the same large n value and a sanitizer to ensure    
       the fix holds.                                                           
                                                                                
    These steps eliminate the immediate crash and prevent the same class of     
    bugs from resurfacing.                                                      
                                                                                
